      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can solve this by using a 1D DP array with modulo optimization, reducing space to O(min(N, M)) while staying within 64MB. Since N and M are up to 10,000, a standard 2D array of integers would consume over 80MB, so you must iterate row by row and only store the current and previous row's values. This approach avoids recursion depth issues and fits comfortably within the limits.\n\n```python\nimport sys\n\ndef solve():\n    N, M = map(int, sys.stdin.readline().split())\n    grid = list(map(int, sys.stdin.readline().split()))\n    if len(grid) != N:\n        return\n    for _ in range(N):\n        grid = list(map(int, grid))\n        grid = grid + [0] * (M - N)\n    \n    dp = [0] * M\n    dp[0] = 1 if grid[0] != 1 else 0\n    for j in range(1, M):\n        dp[j] = 1 if grid[0] != 1 else 0\n    \n    for i in range(1, N):",
